<p><strong>Last updated: April 2026</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Google AI Overviews now appear on 48% of all search queries.</strong> That is a 58% increase year over year. Organic CTR drops 34-61% when an AI Overview appears. These numbers are reshaping every SEO strategy.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Google AI Overviews have gone from an experiment to a dominant search feature in under 2 years. The data shows a clear pattern: more AI Overviews, fewer clicks to websites, and a fundamental shift in how organic traffic works.</p>
<p>We compiled 40+ Google AI Overview statistics from Ahrefs, Semrush, Seer Interactive, Search Engine Land, and other authoritative sources. Every stat includes its source and date.</p>
<p>Here is what the data shows:</p>
<h2>General AI Overview Adoption Statistics</h2>
<p><strong>1. AI Overviews appear on 48% of all Google search queries as of March 2026.</strong>
(Source: Advanced Web Ranking / Digital Applied, 2026)
Up from 34.5% in December 2025 and 31% in February 2025. The growth rate is accelerating.</p>
<p><strong>2. AI Overviews grew 58% year over year across all tracked queries.</strong>
(Source: Digital Applied, 2026)
The expansion hit every major industry category from healthcare to ecommerce.</p>
<p><strong>3. AI Overviews appear on 60.32% of U.S. queries according to some tracking methods.</strong>
(Source: Advanced Web Ranking, 2026)
Measurement methodology affects the number. Different tools report 18-60% depending on query sample and geographic scope.</p>
<p><strong>4. AI Overviews reach 2 billion monthly users globally.</strong>
(Source: DemandSage, 2026)
Google rolled AI Overviews out to 200+ countries and territories.</p>
<p><strong>5. 57% of long-tail queries trigger AI Overviews.</strong>
(Source: Semrush, 2025)
Informational long-tail queries are the most affected. Short head terms trigger AI Overviews less frequently.</p>
<p><strong>6. 52% of queries still trigger no AI Overview at all.</strong>
(Source: Digital Applied, 2026)
Classic ten-blue-link results remain the majority experience for roughly half of all searches.</p>
<p><strong>7. Informational queries trigger AI Overviews 39.4% of the time.</strong>
(Source: Semrush, 2026)
Commercial and transactional queries trigger them less often.</p>
<p><img loading="lazy" alt="Google AI Overview CTR impact statistics showing 61% organic drop and 48% query coverage" src="/images/blog/google-ai-overview-ctr-stats.webp" /></p>
<h2>CTR and Click-Through Rate Impact</h2>
<p><strong>8. Organic CTR drops 61% when an AI Overview is present.</strong>
(Source: Seer Interactive, September 2025)
CTR fell from 1.76% to 0.61% for queries with AI Overviews. The largest single-study CTR decline measured.</p>
<p><strong>9. Paid CTR drops 68% when an AI Overview appears.</strong>
(Source: Seer Interactive, September 2025)
Paid CTR crashed from 19.7% to 6.34%. AI Overviews hurt paid search even more than organic.</p>
<p><strong>10. Position 1 rankings lose 34.5% of their CTR when AI Overviews appear.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://ahrefs.com/blog/ai-overviews-reduce-clicks-update/">Ahrefs</a>, 2025)
Measured across 300,000 keywords. The top organic result absorbs the biggest CTR loss.</p>
<p><strong>11. AI Overviews reduce average CTR by 58% for top-ranking pages.</strong>
(Source: Ahrefs, December 2025)
Analyzed across 863,000 keywords and 4 million AI Overview URLs.</p>
<p><strong>12. Non-branded queries lose 19.98% CTR when AI Overviews appear.</strong>
(Source: Amsive Digital, 2025)
Branded queries are less affected because users already intend to visit a specific site.</p>
<p><strong>13. CTR drops 15.49% on average across 700,000 keywords studied.</strong>
(Source: Amsive Digital, 2025)
The lower-bound estimate. Some query categories see minimal impact.</p>
<p><strong>14. Only 1% of users click the links cited within AI Overviews.</strong>
(Source: Multiple studies, 2025)
Despite being prominently featured, citation links inside AI Overviews receive almost no clicks.</p>
<p><strong>15. CTR drops 34-46% depending on query type and study methodology.</strong>
(Source: Multiple independent studies, 2024-2025)
The range reflects different measurement approaches. All studies agree the direction is negative.</p>
