<h2>Zero-Click and Traffic Impact Statistics</h2>
<p><strong>16. 60% of Google searches now end without a click to any website.</strong>
(Source: SparkToro / Datos, 2025)
Up from 58% in 2024. The zero-click trend predates AI Overviews but accelerated with them.</p>
<p><strong>17. <a href="/blog/zero-click-search-seo/">Zero-click searches</a> reached 69% between May 2024 and May 2025.</strong>
(Source: The Digital Bloom, 2025)
The sharpest year-over-year increase in zero-click rate on record.</p>
<p><strong>18. 43% of all Google searches end without a click to an external website.</strong>
(Source: Multiple sources, 2026)
Rises to 93% when Google AI Mode is active.</p>
<p><strong>19. 93% of searches end without a click when AI Mode is active.</strong>
(Source: Multiple sources, 2026)
Google AI Mode is a more aggressive AI search experience separate from AI Overviews.</p>
<p><strong>20. CTR drops to just 8% when AI Overviews are present vs 15% for traditional results.</strong>
(Source: Multiple studies, 2025)
The absolute CTR numbers show how much search behavior has shifted toward zero-click.</p>
<p><strong>21. The median publisher experienced a 10% year-over-year traffic decline in H1 2025.</strong>
(Source: The Digital Bloom, 2025)
Non-news content sites dropped 14%. News publishers dropped 7%.</p>
<p><strong>22. HubSpot lost an estimated 70-80% of organic traffic.</strong>
(Source: Multiple industry analyses, 2025)
One of the most cited examples of <a href="/blog/ai-search-changing-seo/">AI search impact on major publishers</a>.</p>
<p><strong>23. CNN experienced a 27-38% organic traffic decline.</strong>
(Source: Multiple industry analyses, 2025)
News and media publishers face some of the steepest declines.</p>
<p><strong>24. Even queries without AI Overviews saw a 41% CTR decline.</strong>
(Source: Seer Interactive, 2025)
The CTR decline is not limited to AI Overview queries. User behavior is shifting across all search.</p>
<h2>Citation and Source Statistics</h2>
<p><strong>25. Only 38% of pages cited in AI Overviews also rank in the top 10.</strong>
(Source: Ahrefs / <a href="https://almcorp.com/blog/google-ai-overview-citations-drop-top-ranking-pages-2026/">ALM Corp</a>, 2026)
Down from 76% just 7 months earlier. Google is pulling citations from a wider range of sources.</p>
<p><strong>26. Brands cited in AI Overviews earn 35% more organic clicks.</strong>
(Source: Seer Interactive, 2025)
Being cited in an AI Overview boosts your organic CTR compared to not being cited.</p>
<p><strong>27. Brands cited in AI Overviews earn 91% more paid clicks.</strong>
(Source: Seer Interactive, 2025)
The citation halo effect benefits paid search even more than organic.</p>
<p><strong>28. YouTube is the most-cited domain in AI Overviews.</strong>
(Source: <a href="https://www.semrush.com/blog/semrush-ai-overviews-study/">Semrush</a>, 2025)
YouTube accounts for 18.2% of all citations from outside the top 100 results.</p>
<p><strong>29. Quora is the second most-cited domain in AI Overviews.</strong>
(Source: Semrush, 2025)
Community-generated content earns citations at a disproportionate rate.</p>
<p><strong>30. Reddit is the third most-cited domain in AI Overviews.</strong>
(Source: Semrush, 2025)
Reddit, Quora, and YouTube dominate AI Overview citations across most query categories.</p>
<p><strong>31. Google properties control 23% of all AI citations.</strong>
(Source: Multiple analyses, 2025)
Including YouTube, Google Blog, and Google Support pages.</p>
<p><strong>32. The top 5 cited domains capture 38% of all citations.</strong>
(Source: Semrush, 2025)
Citation concentration is high. A small number of domains receive the majority of AI Overview references.</p>
<p><strong>33. The top 20 cited domains control 66% of all citations.</strong>
(Source: Semrush, 2025)
The remaining 34% is distributed across thousands of domains.</p>
